"Moratiel R., Durán J.M., Snyder R.L.","Responses of reference evapotranspiration to changes in atmospheric humidity and air temperature in Spain",2010,"Climate Research","44","1",,"27","40",,,10.3354/cr00919,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78650312225&partnerID=40&md5=d2c737e036c9c6a7f4b77fd0625c38d4","Universidad Politécnica de Madrid, Departamento de Producción Vegetal: Fitotecnia, 28040 Madrid, Spain; CEIGRAM, Research Centre for the Management of Agricultural and Environmental Risks, 28040 Madrid, Spain; University of California, Davis, Department of Land, Air and Water Resources, Davis, CA 95616, United States","Moratiel, R., Universidad Politécnica de Madrid, Departamento de Producción Vegetal: Fitotecnia, 28040 Madrid, Spain, CEIGRAM, Research Centre for the Management of Agricultural and Environmental Risks, 28040 Madrid, Spain; Durán, J.M., Universidad Politécnica de Madrid, Departamento de Producción Vegetal: Fitotecnia, 28040 Madrid, Spain, CEIGRAM, Research Centre for the Management of Agricultural and Environmental Risks, 28040 Madrid, Spain; Snyder, R.L., University of California, Davis, Department of Land, Air and Water Resources, Davis, CA 95616, United States","We studied the sensitivity of reference evapotranspiration (ETo) to global warming in Spain at the end of the 21st century. The FAO-56 Penman-Monteith equation was used to estimate ETo, and we examined the sensitivity of the latter to changes in temperature and relative humidity. Changes in stomatal resistance in response to increased CO2 concentration were not evaluated, nor were the changes in wind velocity and solar radiation. Different scenarios were used for estimation of future ET o in different river basins as a consequence of trends in the maximum and minimum temperatures and maximum and minimum humidities during the period 1973-2002, as observed from 38 meteorological stations. The temperature increases ranged between 0.3 and 0.7°C decade-1, and the relative humidities fluctuated between 0.1 and -3.7% decade-1. Four scenarios were simulated that considered the variations in linear tendency of the maximum and minimum temperatures and maximum and minimum relative humidities. The trends of the 4 scenarios were incorporated with the data from 338 agrometeorological stations to estimate future ETo. In all cases, there was an annual increase in ETo of 11, 21, 36 and 7% above the annual ETo (1196 mm) for Scenarios 0, 1, 2 and 3, respectively. The river basin most affected by these changes was the Ebro River valley. The most affected months were May, June, July and August, while the least affected months were November, December and January. © Inter-Research 2010.","Climate change; Evapotranspiration; Relative humidity; Spain; Temperature","Air temperature; Ebro river; Meteorological station; Penman-Monteith equations; Reference evapotranspiration; Relative humidities; River basins; Spain; Stomatal resistance; Temperature and relative humidity; Temperature increase; Wind velocities; Atmospheric temperature; Estimation; Evapotranspiration; Global warming; Rivers; Sun; Water supply; Watersheds; Atmospheric humidity; air temperature; concentration (composition); ecosystem response; estimation method; evapotranspiration; global warming; meteorology; Penman-Monteith equation; relative humidity; river basin; sensitivity analysis; solar radiation; twenty first century; wind velocity; Ebro River; Spain",,,,,,"(2010) Resumen Anual Climatológico del Año 2007, , www.aemet.es, AEMET Agencia estatal de Meteorología, AEMET, Madrid. Available at; Allen, R.G., Pereira, L.S., Raes, D., Smith, M., Crops evapotranspiration. Guidelines for computing crop requirements (1998) Irrigations and Drainage Paper 56, , FAO, Rome; Allen, R.G., Pruitt, W.O., Wright, J.L., Howell, T.A., A recommendation on standardized surface resistance for hourly calculation of reference ET0 by the FAO-56 Penman-Monteith method (2006) Agric. Water Manag., 81, pp. 1-22; Anderson,